T1  - Stochastic Dominance: A Methodological Approach to Enhancing the Conceptual Foundations of Operations Management Theory
AU  - Weeks, James K.
Y1  - 1985/01/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4277336
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1985.4277336
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 31
EP  - 38
VL  - 10
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Production/operations management (POM) research has traditionally preference ordered alternatives based on the expected values of outcomes for decision making under risk problems. The shortcomings of ignoring the uncertainty or variance of outcomes are discussed. A hypothetical example is provided to illustrate multiple moment and stochastic dominance preference ordering approaches and to demonstrate the theoretical superiority of stochastic dominance. Conclusions concerning the applicability of stochastic dominance approaches for POM research are presented.
AB  - Production/operations management (POM) research has traditionally preference ordered alternatives based on the expected values of outcomes for decision making under risk problems. The shortcomings of ignoring the uncertainty or variance of outcomes are discussed. A hypothetical example is provided to illustrate multiple moment and stochastic dominance preference ordering approaches and to demonstrate the theoretical superiority of stochastic dominance. Conclusions concerning the applicability of stochastic dominance approaches for POM research are presented.
